\begin_layout Standard

\size large
Also, there is a relative paper on the intergenerational gender gap.
 However, they used a different data set in Norway.
 Haaland et al (2018), use rich longitudinal registry data between 1970-2009
 which covering the entire Norway to investigate the extent to which the
 gap in employment rates between genders is shaped by the intergenerational
 transfer of gender norm.
 They found that the municipality characteristics and a parsimonious set
 of family measured in children can explain a substantial part of the gender
 gap, especially on female employment.
 What I am looking to investigate is, on the other hand, the intergenerational
 income gap between women and men.
